\f0\fs28 \cf0 The whole point of Scrivener is to make working on a long text easier by allowing you to break it up into smaller pieces. Sometimes, however, you will want to see how those smaller pieces fit into the greater whole. This is where \'93Scrivenings\'94 mode comes in.\
There are two ways of entering Scrivenings mode:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Select a folder or group in the binder that contains text subdocuments and use Scrivenings mode to view all of the documents inside the folder as though they were a single text document. (Note that the text of the folder itself is also included at the top.)\
{\listtext	2.	}Select multiple documents in the binder and use Scrivenings mode to view them as though they were a single document.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 We already tried (1) when we were looking at \'93Editor View Modes\'94, so let\'92s try viewing multiple documents this time:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Click into the outliner in the top editor so that the top editor gets the focus (its header bar turning the system accent colour again).\
{\listtext	2.	}Click on \'93START HERE\'94 at the top of the binder.\
{\listtext	3.	}With the Command key on the keyboard held down, click on \'93Editor View Modes\'94 and \'93Scrivenings\'94, so that all three documents get selected.\
{\listtext	4.	}Click on the Scrivenings mode icon in the view mode control in the toolbar (the leftmost icon in the control, showing the two pieces of paper). All three documents will now be loaded into the editor as a single text.\
